The following was taken directly from my birding notes for this date and location (entered into eBird in 6/20/2020). Weather: Overcast (thin to moderate) most of the morning, mostly clearing in PM. 40s to 70s (deg. F), calm.
SPECIES COMMENTS: This is back when this species was still hard to come by in the OC. My notes stated: "One at Burris Pit/the Santa Ana River just below Lincoln. One of the "white-bellied/"Osprey head appearance" type. Maybe not as Osprey-like as last year's bird here. Eye color seemed dark. Dark upper breast (band), white through rest of breast and belly, with sparse dark brown mottling here and there (< or = to 20% cover). Dirty white on basal 2/3 of tail, with fine dark mottling. Didn't study trailing edge of open wing well, but seemed a bit "ragged" (that is, not consistently the same length/shape in feather types). Watched it harass an AMCO for some time in the Santa Ana River bed, directly east of Burris. Flying in tight circles, even "hovering" overhead, about 75 to 100 feet up. The coot staying underwater (fairly shallow however here). Whenever coot made a brief appearance above water, the eagle would drop, but the AMCO would instantly go under again. Went in for perhaps a few minutes before the BAEA tired out and gave up."
